# Project Guardrails

1. **Always read `.cursor/cursor-helper.md` before starting work.** Also read other `.cursor/*.md` files when they apply to the task (e.g. `.cursor/sandboxer-workflow.md`, project-specific guides).
2. **After any change**, update `.cursor/cursor-helper.md` so it matches the current repo layout, ports, Docker services, scripts, and responsibilities.
3. Never change existing business logic unless the author explicitly approves it.
4. Never remove existing functions unless the author explicitly authorizes removal.
5. Never create new top-level guide files or README files without explicit permission — document in `.cursor/` instead (unless the project already uses an approved doc path).
6. **Tester / QA docs:** use one designated file under `.cursor/` (e.g. `.cursor/tester-guide.md`) — do not scatter tester READMEs.
7. **Docker:** keep services documented clearly (table: path, purpose, port, compose file, how to run/stop). Prefer updating `.cursor/cursor-helper.md`; mirror in `docker/README.md` only when that pattern already exists in the repo.
8. **Scripts:** put repeatable dev/test commands in project shell entrypoints (e.g. `scripts/local-dev.sh` subcommands), not only in chat.
9. **Sandboxer:** local dev uses `./sandboxer`, `./sandboxer --full`, `./sandboxer --stop` (see `.cursor/sandboxer-workflow.md` and `docs/sandboxer.md`). Global CLI: `sandboxer <project>`, `sandboxer-full`, `sandboxer-stop`.
10. **`handoff/`** — see `.cursor/rules/handoff-guardrails.mdc` (read-only client design; use `setupp handoff import` for updates).
11. **Push workflow:** when asked to push, always ask which branch to push first and show the available local branches before running push.
